SIMPLE: wrath
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wrath
<hw>Wrath</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>wrathe</ets>, <ets>wra⟦thorn⟧⟦thorn⟧e</ets>, <ets>wrethe</ets>,
<ets>wr⟦ae⟧⟦edh⟧⟦edh⟧e</ets>, AS. <ets>wr⟦aemac⟧⟦edh⟧⟦edh⟧o</ets>, fr.
<ets>wr⟦amac⟧⟦edh⟧</ets> wroth; akin to Icel. <ets>rei⟦edh⟧i</ets>
wrath. See <er>Wroth</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Violent anger; vehement exasperation; indignation;
rage; fury; ire.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Wrath</qex> is a fire, and jealousy a weed.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When the <qex>wrath</qex> of king Ahasuerus was appeased.</q>
<rj><qau>Esther ii. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now smoking and frothing⟦br⟧
Its tumult and <qex>wrath</qex> in.</q> <rj><qau>Southey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The effects of anger or indignation; the just
punishment of an offense or a crime.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A revenger to execute
<xex>wrath</xex> upon him that doeth evil.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Rom. xiii.
4.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Anger; fury; rage; ire; vengeance; indignation;
resentment; passion. See <er>Anger</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wrath</ent>⟦br⟧

